  2022, 'NSTC 2022 Physics Paper', 'If the current in an ammeter’s coil is doubled, the resulting torque on the coil will be',
  '["unchanged","halved","doubled","quadrupled Time (minutes) 𝐑 (𝐜𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐭𝐬/𝐬)4.00 392"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The torque and current are related as: τ ∝i Thus doubling the current also doubles the torque. PART-3 Given: Mass = 2 × 103kg Height = 36 × 103m Time = 1min = 60s',
  10, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2022-final-physics-2022-b4137e5-part-iii-1', 'published', 'physics-2022-final-physics-2022-b4137e5', 'Physics',
  1, 'Descriptive 1', 'Physics',
  'Descriptive', 'Descriptive', 'Long',
  'Part III', 'Descriptive Questions', 'NSTC',
  2022, 'NSTC 2022 Physics Paper', 'Question No 01: A rocket of constant mass 2.00 x 10^3 kg, is fired vertically upward with constant acceleration. After one minute it reaches a height of 36.0 km and its engine is switched off. Assuming the rocket’s mass and g remain constant, calculate a) the initial acceleration of the rocket b) the maximum height reached. c) the total time of flight. d) the work done by the rocket. (2+3+2+3)',
  '[]'::jsonb, null, 'A) Assuming the rocket starts from rest: S = ut + 1 2anett2 anet = Fthrust M −g M ...(i) anet = 2S t2 = 2(36 × 103) (60)2 = 20ms−2 B) Even after the upward acceleration (engine) stops at 36km the rocket still has some velocity that takes it even further up: v = u + at = 0 + 20 × 60 = 1200 ms−1 Now after the engine is stopped only gravity acts so we have: 2(−g)S = v2 −u2 2(−9.8)(S) = 02 −(1200)2 S = 12002 2 × 9.8 = 73.5km Where the negative sign is taken for any vector downwards. Thus the max height reached from ground is S = 36km + 73.5km ≈110km C) Find the time for the extra height using: v = u + at 0 = 1200 −g(t) gt = 1200 t = 1200 9.8 ≈120s Find the time for the descent next: −S = −1 2gt2 t = s 2S g t = r 2(110 × 103) 9.8 t = 1200 9.8 ≈150s Thus the total time is t = 60s + 120s + 150s ≈330s D) It is important to note that in a close round trip (up and back down) the work done by gravity would be zero. The work would be done by the engine’s thrust though. W = Fthrust × h ..from (i) Fthrust = M(anet + g) = 2 × 103(20 + 9.8) ≈60 × 103N W = 60 × 103 × 36 × 103 = 2.16 GJ Given: Mass = m1, m2 Speed(v1) = 2 × 107m/s Speed v′ 1 =?',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2022-final-physics-2022-b4137e5-part-iii-2', 'published', 'physics-2022-final-physics-2022-b4137e5', 'Physics',
  2, 'Descriptive 2', 'Physics',
  'Descriptive', 'Descriptive', 'Long',
  'Part III', 'Descriptive Questions', 'NSTC',
  2022, 'NSTC 2022 Physics Paper', 'Question No 02: Fast neutrons, mass 𝑚1, with a speed 𝑣1 = 2.0 x 10^7 𝑚/𝑠 are slowed down in a nuclear reactor by elastic collision with the nuclei of a moderator. a) Derive the general expression for the speed 𝑣 of the neutron after collision with a nucleus of mass 𝑚2 which is initially at rest. b) Calculate the speed 𝑣 of a neutron after a single, head on, collision with a Hydrogen nucleus. c) Calculate the speed 𝑣 of a neutron after a single, head on, collision with a Carbon nucleus. d) After many collisions with atoms of the moderator at room temperature, what energy will neutron attain? (4+2+2+2) The masses involved are neutron: 1.0087 amu, hydrogen nucleus: 1.0073 amu; carbon nucleus: 11.9934 amu.',
  '[]'::jsonb, null, 'A) Derive the general expression for the speed v of the neutron after collision with a nucleus of mass m2 which is initially at rest. 1. Conservation of Momentum m1v1 + m2v2 = m1v′ 1 + m2v′ (1) 2. Conservation of Kinetic Energy 2m1v2 1 + 1 2m2v2 2 = 1 2m1v′ 2 + 1 2m2v′ (2) Multiply equation (2) by 2 to eliminate the fractions: m1v2 1 + m2v2 2 = m1v′ 2 + m2v′ (3) 3. Subtract Momentum and Energy Equations Rewriting equation (1) and squaring both sides: (m1v1 + m2v2)2 = (m1v′ 1 + m2v′ 2)2 we use a known trick: subtracting (3) from itself after rearranging terms: m1(v2 1 −v′ 2) = m2(v′ 2 −v2 2) Using the identity a2 −b2 = (a −b)(a + b), we write: m1(v1 −v′ 1)(v1 + v′ 1) = m2(v′ 2 −v2)(v′ 2 + v2) (4) From equation (1): v1 −v2 = −(v′ 1 −v′ 2) (5) 4. Solve Using Relative Velocity Identity Rewriting: v′ 2 = v1 + v′ 1 −v2 (6) Now substitute equation (6) into momentum equation (1): m1v1 + m2v2 = m1v′ 1 + m2(v1 + v′ 1 −v2) Expand right-hand side: m1v′ 1 + m2v1 + m2v′ 1 −m2v2 (m1 + m2)v′ 1 + m2v1 −m2v2 Now simplify: m1v1 + m2v2 = (m1 + m2)v′ 1 + m2v1 −m2v2 Bring terms to one side: m1v1 −m2v1 + m2v2 + m2v2 −m1v2 = (m1 + m2)v′ Simplify v′ 1 = (m1 −m2)v1 + 2m2v2 m1 + m2 5. Final Expression for v′ v′ 1 = (m1 −m2)v1 + 2m2v2 m1 + m2 (7) B)Find v′ 1 for Collision with hydrogen: Given Hydrogen Mass m2: 1.0073 amu Neutron m2: 1.0087amu 1 amu ≈1.6 × 10−27 kg Plug this in equation 7: v′ 1 = 1.6 × 10−27(1.0087 −1.0073)2 × 107 + 2(1.0073 × 1.6 × 10−27)(0) 1.6 × 10−27(1.0073 + 1.0087) ≈14 km/s C)Find v′ 1 for Collision with Carbon: Given Carbon Mass m2: 11.9934 amu Neutron m2: 1.0087amu 1 amu ≈1.6 × 10−27 kg Plug this in equation 7: v′ 1 = 1.6 × 10−27(1.0087 −11.9934)2 × 107 + 2(11.9934 × 1.6 × 10−27)(0) 1.6 × 10−27(11.9934 + 1....',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2022-final-physics-2022-b4137e5-part-iii-3', 'published', 'physics-2022-final-physics-2022-b4137e5', 'Physics',
  3, 'Descriptive 3', 'Physics',
  'Descriptive', 'Descriptive', 'Long',
  'Part III', 'Descriptive Questions', 'NSTC',
  2022, 'NSTC 2022 Physics Paper', 'Question No 03: The table below shows measurements of the decay rate of a sample of 128I, a radionuclide often used medically as a trace to measure the rate at which iodine is absorbed by the thyroid gland. a) Write an expression for the activity of the radionuclide as a function of time. b) What is half-life, and decay constant of the radioactive decay? c) What is the relationship between half-life, and decay constant of the radioactive decay? d) Use above data to find the decay constant and half-life of 128I. (2+2+1+5)',
  '[]'::jsonb, null, 'A) We know: N = N0e−λt −dN dt = λN −dN dt = λ(N0e−λt) Let R = −dN dt and R0 = λN0. Thus, R = R0e−λt (1) B) Half-life (T 1 2 ) : ”The time required for half of a radioactive substance to decay.” Decay constant (λ): ”The probability per unit time that a nucleus will decay.” C) Solving: N = N0e−λt 2N0 = N0e −λ(T 1 2 ) 2 = e −λ(T 1 2 ) 2 = e +λ(T 1 2 ) ln 2 = λ(T 1 2 ) T1/2 = ln 2 λ D) To Solve this plug any two values in from the table into (1): 392.2 = R0e−λ(4.00×60) (2) 65.5 = R0e−λ(68.00×60) (3) Dividing equation 2 and 3. 392.2 65.5 = R0e−λ(4.00×60) R0e−λ(68.00×60) 6 = e−240λ+4080λ 6 = e3840λ ln 6 = 3840λ λ ≈4.66 × 10−4s−1 Solving For T 1 2 : T1/2 = ln 2 4.66 × 10−4 ≈1500 s',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
